{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "The authors repeatedly - and wrongly - claim that there is a tradition of Stoic logic (and Stoic logical terminology) transmitted continuously from antiquity to the 19th century that was generally known in the 18th and 19th centuries.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "In this second part of the refutation it is shown that the authors are mistaken on these points, and why.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "They assume that in 19th (and presumably early 20th) century Germany, if a theory is generally known and available, then reference to its author is not required.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Let us agree on this for argument's sake, although general scholarly practice in the late 19th and early 20th centuries does not fully bear this out.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "(ii) Stoic logic was part of the traditional view;",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "However, as this second part of the Refutation will show, (ii) is false, and because of this the authors' argument fails regardless.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "On p.437 we find the - entirely unsubstantiated - claim that '[t]here are many philosophers who paved the way for the revolution in logic in the nineteenth century, and who were (a) either well-informed about Stoic logic and referred to relevant sources in their works (e.g. cf. van Calker 1822; Hamilton 1863, Sigwart 1871, 1873) or (b) made use of Stoic ideas without knowing their origin' (bracketed letters mine).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "So given this complete absence of Stoic logic proper in Pre-Prantlian logic textbooks in 19th century Germany (and beyond), the authors' point (a) above collapses, as does the authors' inference that 'in Frege's time various pieces of Stoic logical thinking were, so to speak, 'in the air'' (p.437, fn. 9, my emphasis).",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "The authors repeatedly refer to this hypothesis that in the 18th and 19th centuries many philosophers and logicians made use of ideas of Stoic logic proper without knowing that they are Stoic.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "What all these claims have in common is that, in their article, the authors do not offer a single concrete piece of evidence or illustration, of what they have in mind.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "The claim of the alleged incorporation of Stoic ideas of logic in many logic textbooks in the (eighteenth and) nineteenth centuries is the result of a once very common confusion between the following two distinct families of theories: Stoic propositional logic and Peripatetic-Platonist hypothetical syllogistic.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "On the one hand, there is the original Stoic syllogistic, which includes a Gentzen-style deductive system of sequent logic built from axiomatic sequences, a negation rule, a simple cut rule, and two further rules (most likely two more complex cut rules), iterative definitions of operators and of non-simple propositions, a formal notion of validity, as well as a basic notion of completeness, a variable-sharing requirement, and a lot more that shows Stoic awareness of essential elements of formal propositional logics.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "On the other hand, there is later Peripatetic-Platonist hypothetical syllogistic.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "This hypothetical syllogistic has none of the above features and contains virtually no Stoic terminology.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "So the authors' claim (b) is simply incorrect.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "It can be concluded that the authors' claims (b) that 19th century logicians (other than Frege and Prantl and Sigwart where he draws on Prantl) 'made use of Stoic ideas without knowing their origin', that in the 19th century Stoic logic was 'a widely known traditional view', that 'several textbooks on logic in the nineteenth century are full of Stoic terminology', and that 'pieces of [proper] Stoic logic[…] were, so to speak, 'in the air'', and that 'Frege saw his conception of logic as competitive with and superior to the Stoics, and therefore cannot be seen as someone who reinvented or plagiarized Stoic logic' are each and every one without any foundation in our evidence and cannot be used as sound reasons against the fact that in his later work Frege lavishly borrowed from (proper) Stoic logic as he found it in Prantl's chapter on the Stoics, including the copious footnotes.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
