      "label": "claim"
    },
    "6": {
      "text": "It is true that between the second century BCE and the third century CE some Stoic logic was fed into the development of the Peripatetic and then Platonist hypothetical syllogistics.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "7": {
      "text": "at the end of antiquity with perhaps one or two exceptions, all terms of hypothetical syllogistic are non-Stoic. They were deliberately replaced with Peripatetic and Platonist terms, based on Greek words present in Aristotle's logic and Plato's dialogues",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "8": {
      "text": "So although propositional logic may have been floating somewhere in the German air at Frege's time, there was nothing floating that was even remotely as close to Frege's late work in philosophical logic and philosophy of language than what he found in Prantl's chapter, including the copious footnotes.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
